The paper deals with the complexity of evaluating first-order queries on structures of bounded degree, which is a topic in both logic (cs.LO) and databases (cs.DB). The use of a dynamical process to evaluate queries suggests a connection to algorithms and data structures (cs.DS), while the mention of a result on model-checking implies a connection to computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the study of structures of bounded degree may also be relevant to discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
